subSection.paragraph: Kalihinane diterpenes Configuration determination Cytotoxicity
ABSTRACT

Eight unreported α -acyloxy amide substituted kalihinane diterpenes, named kalihiacyloxyamides A-H were isolated from the South China Sea sponge
Acanthella cavernosa
. The planar structures and absolute configurations were elucidated by detailed 1D and 2D NMR experiments along with HRESIMS analysis, single crystal X-ray diffraction and CD spectroscopic analysis. Two compounds showed significant cytotoxicity against K562 cell line with IC 50 values of 6.4 and 6.3 μM, while two other compounds displayed moderate cytotoxicity against MDA- MB-231 with IC 50 values of 7.3 and 7.9 μM.

Diterpenes bearing a variable set of nitrogenous functional groups including isonitrile (–NC), isothiocyanate (–NCS), isocyanate (–NCO), and formamide (–NHCHO) functionalities have been found in many marine sponges such as
Acanthella sp.
( Chang et al., 1984 ; Patra et al., 1984 ),
Halichondria sp.
( Molinski et al., 1987 ),
Adocia sp.
( Baker et al., 1976 ),
Ciocalypta sp.
( Wattanapiromsakul et al., 2009 ),
Stylissa cf. massa ( Chanthathamrongsiri et al., 2012 )
,
Cymbastela hooperi ( Wolf and Schmitz, 1998 )
,
Phakellia pulcherrima ( Lamoral-Theys et al., 2011 )
, and
Pseudoaxinella flava ( Wright and Lang-Unnasch, 2009 )
. These and related molecules showed highly diverse and promising biological activities such as cytotoxic ( Sun et al., 2009 ; Xu et al., 2012a ), antimalarial ( Miyaoka et al., 1998 ), antifouling ( Okino et al., 1995 , 1996 ), antimicrobial ( Chang et al., 1987 ; Yang et al., 2006 ), antifungal ( Xu et al., 2012b ), and anthelmintic activities ( Alvi et al., 1991 ). Interestingly, the members of nitrogenous diterpenes, kalihinane diterpenoids were mainly isolated from the
Acanthella
genus, such as Kalihinol A, first example reported in 1984 from Apra Harbor Guam ( Chang et al., 1984 , 1987 ; Patra et al., 1984 ). Since the later, a number of derivatives have been isolated from the genus ( Emsermann et al., 2016 ; Xu et al., 2012a , 2012b ). These kalihinane diterpenoids composed of cis- or trans- decalin mother nuclei with either tetrahydropyran or tetrahydrofuran ring and substituted with nitrogenous residues.

In our previous study, we had reported the isolation of seven unreported diterpenes kalihioxepanes A-G from the sponge
Acanthella cavernosa Dendy (Dictyonellidae)
collected in 2012 ( Wang et al., 2022 ). In the further course of our project on discovering bioactive compounds from the marine sponges of the genus
Acanthella
, eight unreported α -acyloxy amide substituted kalihinane diterpenes, named kalihiacyloxyamides A-H (
1–8
) ( Fig. 1 ) were isolated from
A. cavernosa
collected off Xisha islands in the South China Sea in 2018. Here we describe the isolation, structural elucidation and bioactivity assays.
Kalihiacyloxyamide A ( 1 ) was isolated as a colorless bulk crystal (MeOH). A molecular formula of C 25 H 41 ClN 2 O 4 was established by the

The ESIMS of 1 showed a cluster of isotopic [M +H] + ion peaks at m/z 469 and 471 in a ratio of 3:1, revealed the presence of one chlorine atom in the molecule. The 1 H NMR spectrum in CDCl 3 showed the presence of seven methyl [ δ H 1.19 (3H, s), 1.33 (3H, s), 1.35 (6H, s), 1.41 (3H, s), and 1.42 (6H, s)], an isonitrile-bearing methine [ δ H 4.57 (1H, brs)] and a chlorine-bearing methine [ δ H 3.76 (1H, dd, J =12 Hz, 4.8 Hz)]. The 13 C NMR spectra of 1 displayed 25 carbon resonances for one amide carbon ( δ C 175.5), one isonitrile ( δ C 156.7) ( Chang et al., 1984 ; Patra et al., 1984 ), seven methyls, six methylenes, five methines, and five non-protonated carbons accounted for three unsaturation. In particular, the 1D NMR spectra of
1 in
CDCl 3 contained resonances for a chlorine-bearing tertiary carbon ( δ H 3.76/ δ C 64.5, C-14), an isonitrile-bearing tertiary carbon ( δ H 4.57/ δ C 64.3, C-5), an amide-bearing non-protonated carbon ( δ C 55.4, C-10), four oxygen-bearing non-protonated carbons ( δ C 70.6, C-4; δ C 77.3, C-11; δ C 76.0, C-15; δ C 74.0, C-2 ′ ). The COSY correlations of H 2 -9/H 2 -8/H-7/H-6/H-1/H 2 -2/H 2 -3 and H-5/H-6, together with the HMBC correlations of H 3 -19/C-3, C-4, and C-5, H 3 -20/C-1, C-9, and C-10, H-5/C-1, C-6, and NC, and NH/C-1, C-10, and C-20 indicated the presence of a decalin moiety ( Fig. 2 ). The HMBC correlations from the geminal methyls (H 3 -16 and H 3 -17) to C-14 and C-15, and from H 3 -18 to C-7, C-11, and C-12, COSY correlations of H 2 -12/H 2 -13/H-14 and carbon resonances at δ C 76.0 (C-15) and 77.3 (C-11) revealed the presence of a tetrahydropyran ring in 1 accounted for the remaining unsaturation and connectivity of the two moieties between C-12 and C-7 through the non-protonated carbon C-11. An isobutyl amide group (Substituent a), attached to the decalin ring at C-10, was established by HMBC correlations from the geminal methyls (H 3 -3 ′ and H 3 -4 ′ ) to C-1 ′ and C-2 ′ and from NH [ δ H 6.50 (1H, brs)] to C-1’.

subSection.paragraph: The relative and absolute configuration of 1 was established based on the NOESY ( Fig. 3 ) and single crystal X-ray diffraction. The NOESY correlations of NH/H-1 and H-1/H-7 indicated that these protons were on the same face of the decalin ring and arbitrarily assigned β -orientations. The α -orientations of H-5 and H-6 was determined by the NOESY correlations of H 3 -20/H-6 and H-6/H-5. In addition, the carbon resonances at δ C 41.6 (C-1), 36.6 (C-6), 36.7 (C-9), and 18.9 (C-20) in 1 further confirmed the trans fusion of the decalin ring ( Miyaoka et al., 1998 ; Okino et al., 1995 ; Omar et al., 1988 ). Inspection of the literature data on kalihinols with a Cl-bearing pyran ring indicated that the values of carbon resonance for C-12 is characteristic for determination of the stereochemistry of Cl-14, namely owing to γ- gauche effect, ~28–33 and ~37–40 for axial -Cl and equatorial -Cl, respectively ( Dorman and Roberts, 1970 ; Gueltekin et al., 2008 ; Ribeiro et al., 2000 ; Xu et al., 2012a ). The chlorine atom in 1 was determined to be equatorial by the carbon chemical shifts at δ C 38.3 (C-12). Finally, the absolute configuration of 1 was unambiguously determined as 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , and 14 S by single crystal X-ray diffraction using Cu K α radiation ( Fig. 4 ).

Analysis of the 1D and 2D NMR data revealed that 2 possessed the same carbon skeleton as 1 ( Tables 1 and 3 ). A significant difference between 1 and 2 was found in the chemical shift of C-12 ( δ C 29.1 in 2 instead of δ C 38.3 in 1 ), which was caused by the γ- gauche effect, indicating an axial orientation of Cl-14 ( Dorman and Roberts, 1970 ; Gueltekin et al., 2008 ; Ribeiro et al., 2000 ; Xu et al., 2012a ). The chemical shifts of C-1 to C-10 and NOESY correlations of NH/H-1, H-1/H-7, H 3 -20/H-6, and H-6/H-5 indicated the relative configuration of the decalin ring in 2 was the same as 1 . The relative configurations of C-7 and C- 11 in 2 were determined as S * and R *, respectively, from NOESY correlations of H 3 -18/H-6, H 3 -18/H-8b, and H-8a/H-12, as shown in the Newman projection ( Fig. 3 ).

caption.paragraph: Fig. 2. Key 1 H– 1 H COSY (bold lines) and HMBC (arrows) correlations of 1 , 3 , 5 , and 7 .

subSection.paragraph: According to literature ( Xu et al., 2012a ), the CD spectra of kalihinols is mainly determined by the C-4 and C-5 configuration of them. Thus, the experimental ECD spectra match of 2 with 1 ( Fig. 5 ) assign the absolute configurations of 2 as 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , 14 R .

The 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of 3 and 1 were comparable except for a marked difference in the substituent unit that 3 has one more iso-amyl ester unit than 1 ( Tables 1 and 3 ). The COSY correlations of H 2 -6’/H- 7’/(H 3 -8 ′ and H 3 -9 ′ ) and the HMBC correlations of (H-7 ′ and H 2 -6 ′ )/C-5 ′ , C-8 ′ and C-9 ′ supported the assignment of kalihiacyloxyamide C as 3 ( Fig. 2 ). The location of the iso-amyl ester unit was assigned to be at C-2 ′ by single crystal X-ray diffraction using Cu K α radiation ( Fig. 4 ), and the absolute structure of kalihiacyloxyamide C ( 3 ) was unambiguously determined to be 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , and 14 S .

The carbon skeleton of kalihiacyloxyamide D ( 4 ) was readily assignable as the same as 3 by HSQC, HMBC, and COSY correlations. In particular, the carbon resonances of the decalin ring in 4 were almost superimposable on those of 3 ( Table 3 ), suggesting the same stereostructure of the decalin ring for both 3 and 4 . Differences were observed the signals of C-12 for which the carbon resonance at δ C 38.3 (C-12) in 3 compared to δ C 29.0 in 4 , and indicating an axial orientation of Cl-14 ( Dorman and Roberts, 1970 ; Gueltekin et al., 2008 ; Ribeiro et al., 2000 ; Xu et al., 2012a ). The relative configurations of C-7 and C- 11 in 4 were determined as S * and R *, respectively, from NOESY correlations of H 3 -18/H-6, H 3 -18/H-8b, and H-8a/H-12 ( Fig. 4 ). Finally, the absolute configuration of 4 was determined as 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , and 14 R by comparison with the same experimental ECD spectra of 1 , 3 ( Fig. 5 ) ( Xu et al., 2012a ).

The 1 H and 13 C NMR data of compounds 5 and 6 were similar to compounds 3 and 4 ( Tables 1–3 ), respectively, suggested they were structural analogs, in which an iso-amyl ester group in 3 and 4 was replaced by a phenethyl ester group in 5 and 6 . The phenethyl ester group was determined by a COSY correlation of H-8’/H-9’/H-10 ′ and HMBC correlations of H 2 -6’/C-5 ′ , C-7 ′ , and C-8 ′ , H-9’/C-7 ′ and H-10’/C- 8’ ( Fig. 2 ). The relative configurations of 5 and 6 were established by observation of NOESY correlations of NH/H-1, H-1/H-7, H 3 -20/H-6, H- 6/H-5, H 3 -18/H-6, H 3 -18/H-8b, and H-8a/H-12 ( Fig. 3 ) and the carbon chemical shifts at δ C 38.3 (C-12) in 5 and 29.1 (C-12) in 6 which were found to be the same with 3 and 4 ( Dorman and Roberts, 1970 ; Gueltekin et al., 2008 ; Ribeiro et al., 2000 ; Xu et al., 2012a ). The absolute configuration of 5 and 6 was determined as 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , 14 S and 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , 14 R by comparison with the same experimental ECD spectra of 1 , 3 ( Fig. 5 ).

Most 1 H and 13 C NMR signals for 7–8 were doubled due to the presence of a formamide group ( Tables 2 and 4 ). The 1D NMR signals were separated into the s- cis and s- trans forms based on the formamide chemical shifts as well as HSQC spectra ( Okino et al., 1995 , 1996 ; Xu et al., 2012b ).

Kalihiacyloxyamide G ( 7 ) was isolated as colorless needles (MeOH), and given a C 30 H 50 N 2 O 5 molecular formula based on the HRESIMS (m/z 519.3782 [M + H] + ). The NMR spectra of 7 ( Tables 2 and 4 ) revealed the presence of one formamide group ( δ C 160.3) ( Okino et al., 1996 ), one amide carbon ( δ C 172.6), an ester group carbon ( δ C 171.2), nine methyls [ δ H 0.98 (6H, d, J =6.4 Hz), 1.15 (3H, s), 1.31 (3H, s), 1.36 (3H, s), 1.53 (3H, s), 1.55 (3H, s), 1.57 (3H, s), and 1.61 (3H, s)], one trisubstituted double bond [ δ H 5.70 (1H, brs), δ C 127.5/ δ C 130.8], an oxymethine [ δ H 3.89 (1H, m)/ δ C 83.8], and two oxygenated non-protonated carbons ( δ C 85.9 and 81.3). The COSY correlations of H 2 -9/H 2 -8/H-7/H-6/H-1/H 2 -2/H 2 -3 and H-5/H-6, associated with the HMBC correlations of H 3 -19/C-3, C-4, and C-5, H 3 -20/C-1, C-10, and C-9, H-5/C-1, C-3, C-6 and C-7, and CHO/C-10 indicated the presence of a decalin moiety ( Fig. 2 ). A tetrahydrofuran ring, attached to the decalin ring at C-7, was established by carbon resonances at δ C 85.9 (C-11) and 83.8 (C-14), COSY correlations of H 2 -12/H 2 -13/H-14, HMBC correlations of H 3 -18/C-7, C-11, and C-12 and geminal methyls (H 3 -16 and H 3 -17)/C-14 and C-15, and NOESY correlation between H 3 -18 and H-14. A α -acyloxy amide group (Substituent b) was confirmed by HMBC

The cytotoxicities of compounds 1–8 against the human leukemia K562, normal human hepatocytes L-02, human pancreatic cancer ASPC- 1, human lung carcinoma H69AR, and human breast cancer MDA-MB-231 cell lines were evaluated ( Mosmann, 1983 ; Skehan et al., 1990 ). The bioactive results showed that three compounds exhibited cytotoxicity (IC 50 < 10 μM) against the selected cell lines ( Table 5 ). Compounds 3 and 5 exhibited cytotoxicity against K562 cell line with IC 50 values of 6.4 and 6.3 μM, respectively. The IC 50 values of compounds 5 and 8 against MDA-MB-231 cell line were 7.3 and 7.9 μM, respectively.

In conclusion, we firstly reported eight unreported α -acyloxy amide substituted kalihinane type diterpenoids Kalihiacyloxyamides A-H ( 1–8 ) from the South China Sea sponge
A. cavernosa .
The structures including absolute configurations were elucidated by combined methods such as 1D and 2D NMR experiments, HRESIMS analysis, single crystal X-ray diffraction, and some reported rules. Compounds 3 , 5 , and 8 exhibited significant cytotoxity against K562 and MDA-MB-231 cell lines with IC 50 values ranging from 6.3 to 12.5 μM
.

NMR spectra were measured by Bruker ASCEND TM 400 MHz, Bruker AVANCE III 500 spectrometers and JEOL JNMECP 600. HRESIMS spectra were measured on a Micro-mass Q-Tof Ultima GLOBAL GAA076 LC mass spectrometer. Optical rotations were recorded on a Jasco P-1020 digital polarimeter. UV and CD spectra were taken on a Jasco J-810 spectropolarimeter. X-ray data were obtained by a Bruker APEX-II CCD diffractometer using graphite monochromated Cu-K α radiation. Column chromatography (CC) was performed with silica gel (100–400 mesh, Qingdao Marine Chemical Inc., Qingdao, P. R. China ), ODS silica gel (50 μm, Merck). HPLC was performed on a Waters 2695/ 2998 instrument with DAD detector, equipped with an analytic reversed-phased column (ZORBAX 80 A Extend-C18, 250 × 4.6 mm , 5 μm, 1.0 mL/min). Semi-preparative HPLC used an ODS column [YMC- Pack ODS-A, 10 × 250 mm , 5 μm, 1.5 mL/min].

The marine sponge
Acanthella cavernosa Dendy (Dictyonellidae)
was collected off Xisha islands in the South China
Sea (
111 ◦ 42 ′ E
,
16 ◦ 33 ′ N
) at a depth of
20 m
on
July 3rd, 2018
and was identified by Nicole J. de Voogd , National Museum of Natural History , The Netherlands. A voucher sample (No. XS-2018-18) was deposited at Key Laboratory of Marine Drugs , Chinese Ministry of Education , School of Medicine and Pharmacy, Ocean University of China, China
.

Marine sponge ( 5.5 kg , wet weight) was homogenized and extracted with MeOH (20 Lx4), and then the concentrated residue ( 204 g ) was dissolved in MeOH (1 L) to remove salts. The MeOH solution was evaporated under vacuum to yield a crude extract ( 82 g ). The crude extract was suspended in H 2 O (1 L), which was then extracted with EtOAc (1 L) for three times to yield the EtOAc soluble extract ( 32 g ). The extract was fractionated by silica gel CC and eluted using petroleum ether-acetone (20:1, 10:1, 5:1, 3:1, 1:1, acetone, v/v) and CH 2 Cl 2 –MeOH (10:1, 5:1, 3:1, 1:1, MeOH, v/v) to obtain eleven fractions (Ac.1-Ac.11). Ac.8 ( 0.64 g ) was separated on silica gel CC eluting with petroleum ether-acetone (8:1 and 5:1, v/v) to give subfractions Ac.8.1-Ac.8.5. Ac.8.2 ( 249 mg ) was separated by MPLC (C-18 ODS) with MeOH/H 2 O (85:15, v/v) to yield seven subfractions (Ac.8.2.1 to Ac.8.2.7). Ac.8.2.3 ( 15.4 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (65:35, v/v) to obtain compound 3 ( 12.3 mg , tR =56 min). Ac.9 ( 2.76 g ) was fractionated on silica gel CC eluting with petroleum ether-acetone (10:1 and 5:1, v/v) to give subfractions Ac.9.1-Ac.9.4. Ac.9.2 ( 1.24 g ) was separated by MPLC (C-18 ODS) with MeOH/H 2 O (75:25, v/v) to yield five subfractions (Ac.9.2.1 to Ac.9.2.5). Ac.9.2.2 ( 287 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (65:35, v/v) to obtain compound 4 ( 55 mg , tR = 38 min). Ac.9.2.3 ( 168 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (65:35, v/v) to yield three subfractions (Ac.9.2.3.1 to Ac.9.2.3.3). Ac.9.2.3.3 ( 19.7 mg ) was purified by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (55:45, v/v) to obtain compounds 8 ( 9 mg , tR = 95 min) and 5 ( 5.3 mg , tR = 105 min). Ac.10 ( 1.75 g ) was separated on silica gel CC eluting with petroleum ether-acetone (6:1, v/ v) to give subfractions Ac.10.1-Ac.10.5. Ac.10.3 ( 583 mg ) was separated by MPLC (C-18 ODS) with MeOH/H 2 O (75:25, v/v) to yield five subfractions (Ac.10.3.1 to Ac.10.3.5). Ac.10.3.4 ( 129 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (65:35, v/v) to obtain compound 6 ( 3.7 mg , tR = 33 min). Ac.10.3.5 ( 75.8 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (55:45, v/v) to obtain compound 7 ( 3.2 mg , tR = 65 min). Ac.11 ( 1.93 g ) was fractionated on silica gel CC eluting with petroleum ether-acetone (5:1, v/v) to give subfractions Ac.11.1-Ac.11.7. Ac.11.6 ( 1.08 g ) was separated by MPLC (C-18 ODS) with MeOH/H 2 O (70:30, v/v) to yield five subfractions (Ac.11.6.1 to Ac.11.6.5). Ac.11.6.2 ( 110 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (50:50, v/v) to obtain compound 1 ( 48 mg , tR = 28 min). Ac.11.6.1 ( 166 mg ) was fractionated by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (50:50, v/v) to yield six subfractions (Ac.11.6.1.1 to Ac.11.6.1.6). Ac.11.6.1.4 ( 14.8 mg ) was purified by semi-preparative HPLC eluted with CH 3 CN/H 2 O (40:60, v/v) to obtain compound 2 ( 11.8 mg , tR =46 min).

Kalihiacyloxyamide A ( 1 ) was obtained colorless crystal from MeOH using the vapor diffusion method. The orthorhombic crystal (0.20 × 0.15 × 0.10) was measured on a Bruker APEX-II CCD diffractometer with Cu-K α radiation at 150 K. Crystal data of 1 : empirical formula C 25 H 41 ClN 2 O 4 , M =469.05; space group P 212121 , unit cell dimensions a = 6.7943 (2) Å, b = 8.5259 (2) Å, c = 44.4580 (11) Å, α = β = γ = 90.00 ◦ , V = 2575.34 (12) Å 3 , Z = 4, Dcalcd = 1.210 g cm 3 , μ = 1.565 mm 1 , F (000) =1016.0; a total of 16,312 reflections were collected in the range of 3.974 ◦ < 2
θ <
